gomodel:SYNGO_817  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: The taurine transporter is an integral membrane protein (see reference) and localizes in cultured striatal neurons to cell bodies and dendrites (co-localization with MAP2).\n\nAntibody: rabbit anti-taurine transporterserum Tau11-A (DPC Biermann, Bad Nauheim, Germany,1 : 500); No KO control.\n\n21/8/2017 Pim\n- The synapse localization is in part evidenced by the effect of the TAUT KO on synapse physiology. This means that the dendritic localization is \"postsynaptic\".\n- Based on the known transmembrane topology of the protein, the \"integral component of ... membrane\" term was chosen.. Experimental description: Acutely isolated neurons were obtained from 6- to11-week-old TAUT knockout (KO, n = 11) and wild-type(WT, n = 10) mice, while primary cultures were madefrom newborn TAUT KO (n = 30) and WT (n = 27)mice." , "Automated change 2024-03-14: GO:0099055 replaced by GO:0045211" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7351-8706" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0938-8534" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0755-5899" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3185-5709" ;
        dc:date           "2024-03-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_817" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

